The paper deals with the parameterized complexity of the graph isomorphism problem in the context of tree decompositions, which is a topic related to discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and data structures (cs.DS). The use of the Weisfeiler-Lehman algorithm also suggests a connection to computational complexity (cs.CC) and computational geometry (cs.CG). Finally, the paper provides a unified explanation for various isomorphism results, which could be relevant to logic in computer science (cs.LO).
